Tutorial

Try-Catch-Finally Statements

7 steps

In this tutorial, we will build a basic web application that calculates the Fibonacci Sequence. We will integrate Try-Catch-Finally Statements to help us handle any erroneous data input by the user.

The Fibonacci Sequence, a distinctive mathematical series, is derived by adding the last two numbers in the sequence. Consequently, the numbers within this sequence are positive whole values. Given our understanding of these requirements, it is important to acknowledge that users may occasionally input invalid numbers or characters into our web application.

To address this situation, we will employ Try-Catch Statements, which enable us to detect and handle these invalid inputs appropriately. Without further delay, let us commence our journey to refine our data validation skills through the application of Try-Catch statements in JavaScript.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

JavaScript Basics

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to

  1. Use Try Catch statements
  2. Raise error when doing validation checks
  3. Handle the error raised in the catch block
  4. Create a simple web application to calculate the Fibonacci Sequence

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 7

  • Step 1: Project Setup

    We will be using VanilaJS to build our web application. Before we start coding, let us set up our workspace to build our web application. Create a folder named try-catch. Within this folder, create 3 files, one for each language (HTML, CSS, JavaScript). The three files to create are index.html, index.css and index.js.

  • Step 2: Web Application Structure (HTML)

    Now, open the index.html file and add the code below.

    <!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>

  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Fibonacci Calculator</title>
  <link rel=stylesheet href="./index.css">
  <script src="./index.js" defer></script>
</head>

<body>
  <div id="inner-container">
    <h1>Fibonacci</h1>
    <p>Fibonacci is a sequence of numbers where each number is the sum of the two preceding ones, starting from 0
      and 1. Enter a number to get the Fibonacci sequence up to that number.</p>
    <input type="number" id="input" placeholder="Enter a number">
    <p id="output"></p>
    <div id="button-container">
      <button id="button">Get Fibonacci</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>

</html>
    HTML

    The code above is the main structure we will be using for this web application. The HTML code above is a basic HTML document which will have the bare necessities for us to demonstrate obtaining a text input from the user and displaying the output to our user.

    In lines 9 and 10, we will reference the files we need for our web application. These files have been already created in the previous step. In line 18, we can obtain a numeric input from the user using the <input/> element. By setting the “type” of the input to “number”, we will be able to define what is the data type we are expecting to receive. However, this does not mean that it will block any non-numerical characters. As such, we will need to use “try-catch” statements for error handling.

    Similar to the previous tutorial, in line 19, we have an empty <p> element which will be used to display the output of our code. Lastly, in line 21 we will create a button to execute the code from step 4.

  • Step 4: JavaScript Logic

    Now, we will work on the logic of the application. Essentially, the logic of this application is whenever the user clicks on the button, we will obtain the string of numbers that the user has keyed in and convert the entire string into an array. Add the code below in the index.js file. 

    document.getElementById('button').addEventListener('click', function() {
  let input = document.getElementById('input').value;
  let output = document.getElementById('output');
let sequence = [];
})
    JavaScript

    In line 1, we added a listening event to the button which listens for a button click. Then in line 2, we can obtain the number the user has typed into the <input> element.

  • Step 5: Try-Catch Statements

    We will now learn the syntax of a Try-Catch statement. Below is an example of how a Try-Catch statement should look like.

    try {
 // Code that may throw an exception
} catch (error) {
 // Code to handle the exception
} finally {
 // Code that is always executed
}

    The try-catch statement is used to handle exceptions and control the flow of execution when an exception occurs. It consists of three blocks: try, catch, and finally.

    The try block contains the code that may throw an exception. It is the block where you want to monitor for exceptions.

    The catch block is executed when an exception is thrown within the try block. It takes an error parameter that represents the caught exception. Inside the catch block, you can write code to handle the exception, log error messages, or perform any necessary cleanup actions.

    The finally block is optional and follows the try-catch block. It is always executed, regardless of whether an exception occurred or not. You can use the finally block to perform any necessary cleanup actions, such as closing resources, releasing memory, or restoring the program state.

    Try-catch statements are essential for writing robust code. They allow you to catch any errors that might occur within a crucial process. For example, in an e-commerce platform context, when a user initiates a purchase of an item, we want to ensure that from start to end, the item will be added to the database. However, if there is an error with the payment process, we want to have a chance to “undo” any changes we have made.

  • Step 6: Application of Try-Catch Statement

    In line 5 of index.js, add the code below.

    try {
    if (input < 0) {
      throw new Error('Input cannot be negative');
    } else if (input === '') {
      throw new Error('Input cannot be empty');
    } else if (isNaN(input)) {
      throw new Error('Input must be a number');
    } else {

    }
    output.innerHTML = sequence.join(', ');

  } catch (error) {
    output.innerHTML = error;
  } finally {
    alert(`The ${input}th number in the fibonacci sequence is ${sequence[input - 1]}`);
  }
    JavaScript

    With our code, we will catch 3 types of errors.

    • Numbers less than 0 (line 6)
    • An empty string input (line 8)
    • Input that is not a numerical value (line 10)

    If the input we receive from the user falls within any of these 3 conditions, lines 7, 9 and 11 will raise an error which is passed to the catch block as an argument. In line 18, we will set the output element “innerHTML” property to the error that was raised.

    Lastly, in the finally block, we will add an alert() prompt to the user that informs them that the sequence has been calculated.

    At this point, your code should look like this.

  • Step 7: Algorithm for a Fibonacci Sequence

    The Fibonacci sequence is a series of numbers where each number is the sum of the two preceding ones. It starts with 0 and 1, and the sequence continues infinitely. Mathematically, the Fibonacci sequence is defined as:

    F(0) = 0

    F(1) = 1

    F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2) for n > 1

    In line 13 of index.js, add the code below.

    for (let i = 0; i < input; i++) {
        if (i === 0) {
          sequence.push(0);
        } else if (i === 1) {
          sequence.push(1);
        } else {
          sequence.push(sequence[i - 1] + sequence[i - 2]);
        }
      }
    JavaScript

    In the code above, we will check for the first 2 cases of the sequence as we need 2 numbers in the sequence to continue with the formula. In line 19, we apply the formula to calculate the next Fibonacci number in the sequence by getting the sum of the last 2 numbers in the sequence.

    In line 23, we will use the .join() method to join the items in the array into a string format. We will need to specify the string we would want to join our items with. This is also known as the delimiter.

    The final code for index.js looks like this.

    With that, we are done with the project. If you open index.html in your web browser, you can enter a number, and it will give you the Fibonacci sequence up to that index.
